      "bodyTr": "Lee's Special Prosecution for Dismissing Public Indictment: Does Postponing It Past the Election Resolve Constitutional Concerns?\n\nPresident Lee Jae-myung stated on the 4th that regarding the special prosecution related to dismissing the public indictment in cases involving him, he asked the ruling Democratic Party to make a judgment after going through a process of gathering public opinion and deliberation on the specific timing and procedures. The presidential office emphasized in this special prosecution that it is important to respect the separation of powers and maintain political neutrality.\n\nHowever, concerns are growing among legal experts and opposition parties that the special prosecution could be used as a political tool. They argue that establishing a special prosecution solely to dismiss charges against a specific politician raises serious constitutional questions about the rule of law and equal protection under the law.\n\nThe timing of the special prosecution is also becoming a point of contention. If the prosecution is postponed until after the next election, critics warn this could actually worsen the constitutional concerns rather than resolve them, as it would appear to be strategically timed for political advantage. Such timing could be perceived as using state power for partisan purposes, which contradicts fundamental principles of constitutional governance.\n\nLegal scholars point out that the special prosecution should follow established legal procedures and be based on objective criteria, not political considerations. Any appearance of using prosecutorial power to benefit a particular politician undermines public trust in the justice system and the rule of law itself.",
